$SLS @Idfkytm it means is that someone sold a 2 buck strike that expires today. If $SLS closes at 2 or higher, the person who sold it has to either give the shares they already have (covered calls) OR buy the shares on the open market at current cost. The person who bought the calls will have paid a premium up front, and then they pay the seller the 2 bucks per share. The seller is now on the hook for paying the difference between the current share price and the premium plus 2 buck strike. There are 4,263,000 shares that will transfer hands at 2 buck strike end of day today, assuming it doesn't tank before then. Assuming ZERO of those shares have been purchased yet, then we will see 4.2M shares be assigned - meaning you must purchase them on the open market because you're now short 4.2M shares.
